column1: What book will win the 2019 National Book Award for fiction?
column5: ['Trust Exercise by Susan Choi', 'Sabrina & Corina: Stories by Kali Fajardo-Anstine', 'Black Leopard, Red Wolf by Marlon James', 'The Other Americans by Laila Lalami', 'Disappearing Earth by Julia Phillips']

column6: Using GoodReads as a proxy for subjective quality (popularity), it's 3.1 (5,163), 4.33 (1,329), 3.49 (9,235), 3.96 (4,043) and 3.87 (6,167). In the case of fiction, I think there is a bias toward promoting good, lesser known work. So, B stands out. I'm taking 10% from A and putting it on B and then taking 5% from C and splitting it over D/E.

Crowd doesn't seem to have any strong leanings. I tried to think about using historical data, but from looking at the National Book Awards website, the judges seem to change every year, which makes it a little harder to believe that past information is predictive of future outcomes. [1] In addition, some have written about how the awards are not a reward for success, which makes it hard to believe that using sales data or book review information is predictive of award outcomes. [2] I looked at a list of winners, and though I think I'm pretty well read, but I don't really recognize many of the more recent winners (post 2000). [3] This is suggestive that this is really not a popularity contest.
